    {
      "id": "8058f532_12c75ba5",
      "file_path": "policy-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/controller/DroolsControllerFactory.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 321,
      "message": "I was thinking along the lines of every event class can have its own filter. So if you had a property like \"topic.events=org.foo,org.bar\" you could have \"topic.org.foo.filter=...\" and/or \"topic.org.bar.filter=...\". I don't have any issues with making a class agnostic filter per topic and getting rid of the list if that is preferred.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 1677,
        "name": "Daniel Cruz",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dc443y@att.com",
        "username": "dc443y"
      },
      "updated": "2019-02-19 18:56:25.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "b9e73fd1_3248717d",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "8ee587c7_00e2c724",
      "file_path": "policy-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/protocol/coders/JsonProtocolFilter.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 140,
      "message": "Yes it can. The original intent was that if there are no rules then there's no need to call any filtering. I originally thought there was a check within the ProtocolCoderToolSet filter() method that checks if there are rules and if there's none then it skips the filter. However, after rechecking per your comments the hasRules() check is for deciding to return the first decoder. I'll update the constructors to add a \".*\" match.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 1677,
        "name": "Daniel Cruz",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dc443y@att.com",
        "username": "dc443y"
      },
      "updated": "2019-02-19 18:56:25.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "55f953ba_2ca69527",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "46a0ad93_cae8c28e",
      "file_path": "policy-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/protocol/coders/JsonProtocolFilter.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 140,
      "message": "or just return true if expression == null\n\ncould do that at the top of the method and avoid using jsonpath altogether in that case",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2019-02-19 19:12:51.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "8ee587c7_00e2c724",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "6f6482fb_3b07a9b0",
      "file_path": "policy-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/controller/DroolsControllerFactory.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 321,
      "message": "What you have is good Daniel, I misread, the 1<->0,1 mapping from class to filter is preserved.  No comment.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 477,
        "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
        "username": "jhh"
      },
      "updated": "2019-02-19 19:42:29.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "8058f532_12c75ba5",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "f43467bf_8ada7f33",
      "file_path": "policy-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/protocol/coders/JsonProtocolFilter.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 140,
      "message": "I agree that checking the expression == null is good here since this is static method can be called from anywhere with an any arbitrary \"expression\" including null.\n\nStill for your consideration, could have \".*\" in the constructor too, and do another check for it before invoking jsonpath library as well.    The nice thing of always having a value attached to the jsonprotocolfilter regardless (in this case the \".*\" matches-all-wildcard) is that you don't have to do any checks for null and may simplify a little the code.  Not sure if in this case how much is the saving so it is for your consideration.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 477,
        "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
        "username": "jhh"
      },
      "updated": "2019-02-19 20:01:41.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "46a0ad93_cae8c28e",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "3793bf2c_16d5dc2d",
      "file_path": "policy-management/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/drools/protocol/coders/JsonProtocolFilter.java",
      "patchset_number": 5,
      "line": 140,
      "message": "that's fine with me, too, though obviously not as efficient.  In that case, I assume we'd just let java throw NPE if expression=null (which is pretty standard)",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
